observations.recommendation:
1. We recommended that the Municipal Mayor issue immediately an Executive Order creating the Inventory Committee and instruct and monitor the Inventory Committee on their compliance with the guidelines and procedures in inventory taking, recognition of those found at the station, and disposition for non-existing and/ missing PPE items for one-time cleansing of PPE as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant prepare a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to:

a) transfer the incomplete projects of ₱ 4,133,415.79 to the respective CIP- PPE accounts unless completed already;

b) derecognize the supplies and materials of ₱773,026.29 recorded as PPE and record the same to the appropriate supplies and inventory account;

c) record the reclassification of CIP-Buildings and Other Structures; and CIP – Infrastructure Assets of ₱ 5,566,560.87 and ₱ 5,366,621.01, respectively, to the appropriate PPE account.

d) record progress billings for PPEs acquired by contract by consistently applying the Construction Period Theory in recording transactions.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor issue a directive to all Heads of Offices in the LGU instructing them that receipt and delivery of all procured supplies and materials should be centralized and handled only by the Property Custodian Officer for monitoring and proper recording of the said assets.

We recommended that the Property Custodian Officer: 

Maintain Stock Cards (Appendix H) and record all supplies upon receipt of deliveries supported with the Acceptance and Inspection Report (Appendix I);

Issue a pre-numbered approved Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS)                   (Appendix J)  when releasing all kinds of supplies and materials to the end-users;

Prepare the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI)                    (Appendix K), duly supported with pre-numbered RIS issued during each month, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant every 1st week of the month to reduce his accountability. 

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Record all supplies in the Inventory account upon purchase;

Record issued supplies in the appropriate expense account based on the  SSMI and RIS from the Supply Officer, and;

Prepare and maintain Supplies Ledger Cards (Appendix L), to record receipts, issuances and balances of supplies procured by the LGU. The SLC must be properly posted and kept updated always to support the Inventory account in the books of the LGU. 

We recommended that the Inventory Committee conduct yearly a physical count of all inventory items and submit a RPCI (Appendix M), to the Municipal Accountant for reconciliation with the balances in the Supplies Ledger Card.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor issue a directive to the following officials and monitor their compliance with the following corrective measures:

Mandate the Municipal Assessor to prepare and submit to the Municipal Treasurer, on or before the thirty-first (31st) day of December each year, an updated Assessment Roll containing the list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed or reassessed and the values of such properties;

Require the Municipal Treasurer to:

furnish the Municipal Accountant with a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year at the beginning of the year as basis to draw a Journal Entry to record the RPT and SET Receivables and its corresponding deferred accounts;

maintain the RPTAR for proper record-keeping of the RPT transactions; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to:

record the receivables from RPT and SET at the beginning of the year upon receipt from the Municipal Treasurer the Certified List of Taxpayers with the amount due for collections; 

review the transactions recorded under the RPT and SET Receivables accounts and its corresponding deferred accounts in the prior years to determine the cause of the discrepancy, and prepare necessary adjusting entries to correct the affected accounts.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor convene the Municipal Development Council annually to review the projects funded from the Continuing Appropriations of the 20% Development Fund and identify which should be prioritized and included in the current year Annual Investment Plan.

We recommended that the Municipal Budget Officer review the balances of the Continuing Appropriation in the preparation of the annual budget so that any amount no longer needed can be reverted to the Unappropriated Surplus of the LGU or be re-appropriated for other development projects that can be implemented during the budget year;

We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer confirm the availability of cash from the Continuing Appropriations of the 20% Development Fund and maintain a separate record to monitor utilization of the equivalent cash to ensure that projects identified in the AIP are adequately funded.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Review and evaluate the workforce of each department to determine their actual personnel needs and create a staffing pattern so that the ideal number of plantilla personnel will be established and vacant positions will be filled-up taking into consideration the Personnel Services limitation;

Limit the hiring of personnel under Job Order/Contract of Service to those extremely necessary and deploy only to offices that actually are in need of their services;

Issue written policies and guidelines on the hiring of JOs as guide in drafting their contracts and in evaluating their accomplishments;

Issue an Executive Order requiring the JO personnel to use the biometrics attendance recording system and require each Office to maintain an attendance logbook indicating respective names and signatures, the time of arrival and departure from the office to support to the manual DTR;

Pay the mandated daily minimum wage of ₱ 375.00 as prescribed by the RTWPB Region 8.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant process payments for the wages of JOs only when supported with DTRs based on biometric print-out, and monthly Accomplishment Report stating the quantifiable output accomplished for a particular period to confirm validity of the expenses.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

submit hard copies of the BRS from January to December 2021 duly supported with copies of bank statements or bank snapshots, cancelled and paid checks, bank debit and credit memos to facilitate the verification of the monthly BRS. Henceforth, prepare all the BRS for each bank account maintained with AGDB and submit to the Audit Team;

Prepare and maintain a separate subsidiary ledger for each bank accounts maintained.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

maintain a separate subsidiary ledger for each PPA implemented by the Municipality;

submit to the Audit Team and Source Agency the: (i) monthly Report on Utilization of fund transfer; (ii) Liquidation Reports of implemented programs/projects

reconcile the balances of each fund transfers made by the Source Agency specifically those which remained unliquidated in the SA’s books but a corresponding liquidation report was already submitted.

secure a certification from the Municipal Accountant of Source Agencies of FTs with submitted liquidation reports;

closely monitor the submission of the liquidation reports and always maintain copies of each report submitted to the Source Agency.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Review current and previous transactions affecting the Construction in Progress accounts to determine possible errors made and to confirm the composition of the accounts;

Reconcile with the records of the Municipal Engineering Office, particularly on-going projects which were previously classified as Construction in Progress and prepare the necessary correcting entries, where necessary;

1. Review current and on-going transactions affecting the Construction in Progress accounts to determine possible errors made and to confirm the composition of the accounts;
2. Reconcile with the account records of the Municipal Engineering Office, particularly on-going projects which were previously classified as Construction in Progress and prepare the necessary correcting entries, where necessary;
3. Maintain an updated Subsidiary Ledger for each project to support the GL balance of CIP account and strictly observe the correct use of the accounts prescribed in the Revised Chart of Accounts for Local Government Units; And disclose the details of CIP accounts in the Notes to the Financial Statements.
